Exercise: Train Logistic Regression models with default parameters

  • based on 3-fold cross validation
  • calculate log_losses as metrics, both on the train and test sets

Let's package the cross validation process into a function of X and y

In [47]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.metrics import log_loss

def cross_val(X, y, model, random_state=42, verbose=False):
    cv = KFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=random_state)
    losses = []
    models = []

    for train_index_set, test_index_set in cv.split(X):
        model.fit(X[train_index_set], y[train_index_set])

        y_pred_proba_test = model.predict_proba(X[test_index_set])
        y_pred_proba_train = model.predict_proba(X[train_index_set])

        test_log_loss = log_loss(y[test_index_set], y_pred_proba_test)
        train_log_loss = log_loss(y[train_index_set], y_pred_proba_train)

        if verbose:
            print(train_log_loss, test_log_loss)
    
        losses.append([train_log_loss, test_log_loss])
        models.append(model)
    
    return losses, models

    losses = []
    models = []

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.metrics import log_loss

def cross_val(X, y, model, random_state=42, verbose=False):
    cv = KFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=random_state)
    losses = []
    models = []

    for train_index_set, test_index_set in cv.split(X):
        model.fit(X[train_index_set], y[train_index_set])

        y_pred_proba_test = model.predict_proba(X[test_index_set])
        y_pred_proba_train = model.predict_proba(X[train_index_set])

        test_log_loss = log_loss(y[test_index_set], y_pred_proba_test)
        train_log_loss = log_loss(y[train_index_set], y_pred_proba_train)

        if verbose:
            print(train_log_loss, test_log_loss)
    
        losses.append([train_log_loss, test_log_loss])
        models.append(deepcopy(model))
    
    return losses, models

Exercise: train a good model using all these 209 features

Remember the idea of regularization to avoid overfitting:

minimize      LogLoss+Kw2iminimize     CLogLoss+w2iminimize      LogLoss+Kwi2minimize     CLogLoss+wi2

We can tune the regularization coefficient CC in the scikit-learn models

Main differences between L1 and L2 regularization

The unit sphere is different in these two metrics, thus the L1-regularization tries to push as many coefficients exactly to zero as possible, while L2 also tries to push them to 0, but not exactly.

Exercise: train some L1 and L2 regularized Linear Regression models on the extended features with different C coefficients and observe the change in the number of exactly 0 coefficients

C=0.001C=0.001 inflicts too much penalty, everything is pushed exactly to 0, the score is terrible, too

C=0.01C=0.01 still inflicts heavy penalties, only a few coefficients can be nonzero, the score is better, but not the best

C=0.1C=0.1 gives more freedom to the model while still pushing a large number of coefficients exactly to 0, while producing one of the best models we could build with this approach.

C=10C=10 allows a lot of the coefficients to be nonzeros

Elastic-Net regularization

minimize     CLogLoss+|wi|+(1)w2iminimize     CLogLoss+|wi|+(1)wi2

While it can be useful to have a lot of exactly zero coefficients the runtime can be much higher for L1 and Elastic-Net regularizations, in most cases it's better to accept the almost-0 coefficients of an L2 regularization

Logistic Regression with multiple classes

If we have 3 classes then the Logistic Regression can be applied to different ways

Option #1: OVR, one-vs-rest approach

We treat the problem as 3 binary classification problems and train different Logistic Regression models on them.

  • Class 1 vs (not Class 1)
  • Class 2 vs (not Class 2)
  • Class 3 vs (not Class 3)

Option #2: minimizing a multinomial loss function

In a binary case we obtained the prediction as

ypred=f(w,x)=(wTx+b)(z)=11+ezypred=f(w,x)=(wTx+b)(z)=11+ez

Now we generalize this by using 33 different weight vectors (with different biases)

z1=wT1x+b1z1=w1Tx+b1 z2=wT2x+b2z2=w2Tx+b2 z3=wT3x+b3z3=w3Tx+b3

Then instead of the sigmoid function we use a generalization of that, the softmax function to get the 33 probabilities to belonging to a class

ypred=[y1,y2,y3]=[ez1ez1+ez2+ez3,ez2ez1+ez2+ez3,ez3ez1+ez2+ez3]ypred=[y1,y2,y3]=[ez1ez1+ez2+ez3,ez2ez1+ez2+ez3,ez3ez1+ez2+ez3]

These are the outputs of the model.predict_proba() function. If we need the class predictions as in model.predict(), we can just find the largest value and predict the corresponding class (np.argmax function)

The logloss function can be extended for this, too (cross-entropy):

(binary case)  LOSS=1nytruelog(ypred)+(1ytrue)log(1ypred)(binary case)  LOSS=1nytruelog(ypred)+(1ytrue)log(1ypred)

The ytrueytrue is encoded as a 0-1 vector, e.g. if the true label is Class 2, then it is ytrue_onehot=[0,0,1]ytrue_onehot=[0,0,1]. Then the summation goes with terms like ytrue_onehot[i]log(ypred[i])ytrue_onehot[i]log(ypred[i])

Example: if the true label is class 2 and we predicted [0.1, 0.3, 0.6] probabilities, then

0log(0.1)+0log(0.3)+1log(0.6)0log(0.1)+0log(0.3)+1log(0.6)

Or if the true label is class 1 and we predicted [0.1, 0.3, 0.6] probabilities, then

0log(0.1)+1log(0.3)+0log(0.6)0log(0.1)+1log(0.3)+0log(0.6)
